<p><strong>California Pocket Mouse (<em>Perognathus californicus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Heteromyidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Perognathus californicus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong> California Pocket Mouse<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The California Pocket Mouse has a length of 3⅕-3⅗ inches, a tail length of 4-5⅘ inches, and an average weight of 23 grams. It has an olive-brown color flecked with tawny and a crested tail that is longer than its body. It also has distinct spinelike hairs on its rump. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=california%20mouse&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This pocket mouse can be found along the coast in the southern part of California on slopes covered with chaparral or live oaks. It is the most common pocket mouse and enters into a state of torpor during periods of low temperature and reduced food supplies. It bears 2-5 young once a year between March and June, and has a gestation period of 25 days.</p>
